What you want is a parallel Cartesian sweep over varList (mixed-radix combinations across block variant counts), with:

No shared state between runs (each run uses its own Placement instance/state),

No locks (work distribution via a single atomic counter; each worker writes to its own result slot),

Fast access from Python (zero-copy NumPy views for summary arrays + a way to re-run any chosen combination to get full history through the existing Runner API),

Per-run runtime + error/log message.

There’s one unavoidable reality:
If you literally have 1000 blocks with up to 50 variants each, the total combinations is astronomically large (50^1000). No system can “run all combinations”. So the API must support:

exhaustive when feasible, else

bounded run count (max_runs) or a sampling/heuristic mode.

Below is a concrete implementation that is still “all combinations” when total_combinations <= max_runs (or when max_runs==0 and total fits a safe bound), but won’t let you accidentally request an impossible sweep.

